Speaker: Dr. Toshiyuki Kaji (RIKEN Center for Advanced Photonics)

Title: "Development of a high-speed 3D imaging system for the analysis of neuronal activity in the whole brain of a small fish"

Abstract: The brain is a complex network of neurons that are connected to each other. To understand the brain function, it is necessary to measure the activity of a large number of neurons simultaneously. In recent years, the development of optogenetics and calcium indicators has made it possible to measure the activity of neurons in the whole brain of small animals such as zebrafish larvae and fruit flies. However, the imaging speed of conventional microscopes is not fast enough to capture the activity of all neurons in the whole brain. In this study, we developed a high-speed 3D imaging system that can capture the activity of all neurons in the whole brain of a small fish at a rate of 100 frames per second. The system uses a combination of light-field microscopy and a high-speed camera to capture 3D images of the brain. We applied this system to the analysis of neuronal activity in the zebrafish brain during various behaviors such as swimming and feeding. Our results show that the system can capture the activity of individual neurons in the whole brain with high temporal resolution, and that the activity patterns of different neurons are correlated with specific behaviors. This system will be a powerful tool for the study of brain function in small animals.

Biography: Dr. Toshiyuki Kaji is a researcher at the RIKEN Center for Advanced Photonics in Japan. He received his Ph.D. in neuroscience from the University of Tokyo in 2010. His research focuses on the development of new imaging techniques for the study of brain function in small animals. He has published numerous papers in leading scientific journals and has received several awards for his work.

The holidays are a time for family, friends, and food. But for many people, the season can also be a time of stress and anxiety. If you’re feeling overwhelmed by the holiday season, here are some tips to help you cope.

1. Set realistic expectations.

The holidays are often portrayed as a time of joy and happiness, but the reality is that they can be stressful and overwhelming. It’s important to set realistic expectations for yourself and your family. Don’t try to do too much or be perfect. Just focus on enjoying the time you have together.

2. Make a plan.

One of the best ways to reduce stress is to have a plan. Make a list of everything you need to do and prioritize the most important tasks. This will help you stay organized and focused.

3. Take breaks.

It’s important to take breaks and relax during the holidays. Make time for yourself and do things that you enjoy. This will help you recharge and be more present for your family and friends.

4. Ask for help.

Don’t be afraid to ask for help. If you’re feeling overwhelmed, reach out to your family and friends for support. They can help you with tasks or just be there to listen.

5. Practice self-care.

Self-care is important all year round, but it’s especially important during the holidays. Make sure you’re taking care of yourself physically and emotionally. Get enough sleep, eat healthy, and exercise. And don’t forget to take care of your mental health. If you’re feeling anxious or depressed, talk to a therapist or counselor.

The holidays can be a difficult time, but with the right strategies, you can cope with the stress and enjoy the season.

The holiday season is a time for family, friends, and of course, food. But with all the delicious treats and meals, it can be easy to overindulge and pack on...

The holiday season is a time for family, friends, and of course, food. But with all the delicious treats and meals, it can be easy to overindulge and pack on a few extra pounds. If you’re looking to stay healthy and fit during the holidays, here are some tips to help you out.

1. Plan ahead.

Before you head to a holiday party or sit down for a big meal, plan out what you’re going to eat. Decide which dishes you want to try and which ones you can skip. This will help you avoid overeating and make healthier choices.

2. Eat before you go.

If you’re going to a party or event where there will be lots of food, eat a small, healthy meal before you go. This will help you avoid overeating and make it easier to resist temptation.

3. Bring a healthy dish.

If you’re going to a potluck or dinner party, bring a healthy dish to share. This way, you’ll know there’s at least one healthy option available.

4. Watch your portion sizes.

It’s easy to overeat during the holidays, so be mindful of your portion sizes. Use a smaller plate and fill it with mostly fruits and vegetables. And remember, you don’t have to finish everything on your plate.

5. Stay active.

Don’t let the holidays be an excuse to skip your workouts. Make time for exercise, even if it’s just a quick walk around the block. This will help you burn off some of those extra calories and keep you feeling energized.

6. Drink plenty of water.

Staying hydrated is important for your overall health, and it can also help you avoid overeating. Drink a glass of water before meals and sip on water throughout the day.

7. Don’t deprive yourself.

It’s okay to indulge in your favorite holiday treats, just do so in moderation. Enjoy a small portion and savor every bite.

By following these tips, you can enjoy the holiday season without sacrificing your health and fitness goals.

The Beatles



The Beatles were an English rock band formed in Liverpool in 1960. With members John Lennon, Paul McCartney, George Harrison and Ringo Starr, they became widely regarded as the greatest and most influential act of the rock era.



The Beatles built their reputation playing clubs in Liverpool and Hamburg over a three-year period from 1960, with Stuart Sutcliffe initially serving as bass player.



The core of Lennon, McCartney and Harrison went through a succession of drummers, most notably Pete Best, before asking Starr to join them.



Manager Brian Epstein molded them into a professional act, and producer George Martin guided and developed their recordings, greatly expanding their popularity in the United Kingdom after their first hit, “Love Me Do”, in late 1962.



As their popularity grew into the intense fan frenzy dubbed “Beatlemania”, the band acquired the nickname “the Fab Four”, with Epstein, Martin, and other members of the band’s entourage sometimes given the informal title of “fifth Beatle”.



The Beatles were international stars by early 1964, leading the “British Invasion” of the United States pop market and breaking numerous sales records.



They soon made their film debut with A Hard Day’s Night (1964). From 1965 onwards, they produced increasingly innovative recordings, including the albums Rubber Soul (1965), Revolver (1966), Sgt. Pepper’s Lonely Hearts Club Band (1967), The Beatles (commonly known as the White Album, 1968) and Abbey Road (1969).



After their break-up in 1970, they each enjoyed successful musical careers of varying lengths.



McCartney and Starr, the surviving members, remain musically active.



According to the RIAA, the Beatles are the best-selling music artists in the United States, with 178 million certified units.



They have had more number-one albums on the British charts and sold more singles in the UK than any other act.



In 2008, the group topped Billboard magazine’s list of the all-time most successful “Hot 100” artists; as of 2016, they hold the record for most number-one hits on the Hot 100 chart with twenty.



They have received ten Grammy Awards, an Academy Award for Best Original Song Score and fifteen Ivor Novello Awards.



The group was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1988, and all four were inducted individually from 1994 to 2015.



They were also collectively included in Time magazine’s compilation of the twentieth century’s 100 most influential people.



In 2014, they received the Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award.

The song was written for and sung by the Beatles’ drummer Ringo Starr as the character “Billy Shears”; it is ranked #311 on Rolling Stone’s list of the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time.



Lennon and McCartney finished writing this in mid-March 1967, written specifically as Starr’s track for the album.
